1
00:00:00,436 --> 00:00:25,801
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa

2
00:00:26,574 --> 00:00:35,307
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:35,326 --> 00:00:47,503
She wants to look at this word, panya, which often comes up alongside, in some form or other, the word sati, which means awareness, but I'll deal with that another time.

4
00:00:48,546 --> 00:00:51,612
So this word paññá, it has two parts to it.

5
00:00:51,692 --> 00:00:58,603
The ñá comes right through the Greek with gnosis and the Latin and ends up with us as no.

6
00:00:59,225 --> 00:01:03,792
It's the same sort of root word which is sort of a sentimental link with the Buddha.

7
00:01:05,897 --> 00:01:10,504
And the pa is just a reinforcing of a really, a really no.

8
00:01:10,525 --> 00:01:13,709
And we tend to translate it as insight.

9
00:01:14,787 --> 00:01:44,322
but in its passive form it's wisdom we refer to it as wisdom and wisdom here isn't to be confused with knowledge in the sense of a cleverness it's the way we relate to life either wisely or unwisely it's a position and this wisdom when it's active becomes an insightful process

10
00:01:45,549 --> 00:02:01,314
So sometimes it's translated as a knowing which is I think a lovely word for it because knowing tells you what it does and it doesn't concretize it into an object.

11
00:02:03,286 --> 00:02:32,905
when we are meditating what we're trying to pull out as it were or make obvious to ourselves is this faculty of Panya is this pure intelligence this intuitive intelligence that we have and it has the reason why we get confused is because

12
00:02:32,968 --> 00:02:41,618
it's always expressing itself through something phenomenal, something that is within the world.

13
00:02:41,739 --> 00:02:45,081
So physical intelligence, you see that in sports people.

14
00:02:45,102 --> 00:02:50,427
I mean, a tennis player might practice a great deal, but on the court there's no thought.

15
00:02:50,868 --> 00:02:53,831
There's just that immediate response.

16
00:02:53,852 --> 00:02:56,395
It's a sort of physical wisdom, you can say.

17
00:02:57,707 --> 00:03:26,584
even just ordinary people, that would be sports people if something comes flying at you, you don't think about it, you just move so that's an intelligence expressing itself through our physical nature the other main one would be an aesthetic intelligence through art and we can see that in people especially who perform they're not thinking, they just do, they've practiced the piece

18
00:03:26,968 --> 00:03:34,936
And then it's just that complete absorption in the expression, whatever they're doing, singing, playing piano, whatever.

19
00:03:36,217 --> 00:03:38,939
And in the intellect, of course, that's the final one.

20
00:03:39,039 --> 00:03:43,462
So you're not...

21
00:03:44,484 --> 00:03:52,431
This intelligence has to express itself, its knowledge, through words as well, through concepts.

22
00:03:54,652 --> 00:03:55,473
And...

23
00:03:56,787 --> 00:04:10,062
Through this process of vipassana, specifically this process of vipassana, we're trying to disembed this intelligence from its confusion with the body, heart and mind.

24
00:04:11,342 --> 00:04:14,826
And that's what we're doing when we make these things an object.

25
00:04:14,887 --> 00:04:22,035
So when we see feelings and sensations, when we're moving around and we're aware of the body moving,

26
00:04:22,689 --> 00:04:32,223
when we are aware of our emotional states, and when we're aware of our images and thoughts, we're aware of something.

27
00:04:32,805 --> 00:04:42,279
So the awareness there, even in the language, tells us that the awareness is something separate, shall we say, from what it's aware of.

28
00:04:43,060 --> 00:04:43,922
And it's making that

29
00:04:44,341 --> 00:04:54,593
It's making everything very clearly an object to ourselves so that this intelligence begins to recognize its own specific quality.

30
00:04:55,713 --> 00:05:04,783
And it cannot know itself in the same way that it can know an object.

31
00:05:05,625 --> 00:05:10,129
So in the Mahayana they'll say, you know, the eye cannot see itself.

32
00:05:10,750 --> 00:05:12,233
The tongue doesn't taste itself.

33
00:05:13,134 --> 00:05:14,095
It's a totally...

34
00:05:14,512 --> 00:05:29,499
it's something which is beyond the phenomenal world I mean can you imagine if your tongue had its root taste had a regular root taste the actual taste of the tongue was curry it'd ruin the porridge wouldn't it?

35
00:05:30,060 --> 00:05:38,935
so it's a case of recognizing that our senses are totally receptive they don't actually come colored you might say

36
00:05:39,050 --> 00:06:06,660
they come with an ability so for instance sight comes with an ability to see but a person may be colour blind but it's still a receptive faculty so this intelligence doesn't this primordial intelligence that we have isn't something which can eventually be described and yet it knows this is the peculiar thing

37
00:06:06,843 --> 00:06:12,232
And it doesn't know what it knows until it expresses what it knows.

38
00:06:12,833 --> 00:06:21,988
So that's why an artist, something like a painter, you know, keeps working with the piece, you see, keeps working with the piece.

39
00:06:22,009 --> 00:06:27,517
And in so doing, this intelligence finds a way of expressing what it knows.

40
00:06:27,598 --> 00:06:47,480
When we're describing something, even now as I'm talking, you see, some of it I might know in the sense of something I've already learnt from the past, but often I find even when I'm talking, I say something in a slightly different way or I say something differently.

41
00:06:47,461 --> 00:07:04,017
which has not been thought out it just comes and I'm sure you've all had the experience of saying something amazingly wise and wondering where it came from so it's that intelligence you see which is within us and the

42
00:07:06,360 --> 00:07:11,988
The last thing to really understand is that this intelligence sparks any time.

43
00:07:12,649 --> 00:07:16,014
The vipassana, the practice of vipassana is just a training.

44
00:07:16,295 --> 00:07:21,581
It's just helping us to discover this original intelligence.

45
00:07:22,663 --> 00:07:24,505
But it sparks off at any time.

46
00:07:26,307 --> 00:07:36,182
It's well known, for instance, in the Mahasi tradition that often insights, deep insights come exactly when you don't expect them, like when you're eating and stuff like that.

47
00:07:37,175 --> 00:07:44,670
Because often our vipassana is distorted by wrong effort, trying to see something, trying to understand something.

48
00:07:46,000 --> 00:08:03,363
So this intelligence we have is the active side of our awareness which is often translated as consciousness, awareness, attention, all that.

49
00:08:03,824 --> 00:08:11,754
All these words in English are all pointing to this faculty, this satipaññā, this awareness, intelligence.

50
00:08:12,545 --> 00:08:17,213
And the awareness is more that receptive nature, the receiving.

51
00:08:17,894 --> 00:08:25,646
When it becomes active, it becomes as a sort of passive action of wisdom, seeing things in a particular way.

52
00:08:26,487 --> 00:08:35,143
And then when an occasion arises, you get this insight, this darting forth, this grasp of something.

53
00:08:36,236 --> 00:09:05,754
and it's not limited to the spiritual life we're talking here about the spiritual life where that darting forth is really to do with understanding these three characteristics because the purpose of our practice is simply to bring an end to suffering but it's there in everything we do is intelligence whether it's opening the bonnet of your car and looking to see what's wrong

54
00:09:06,240 --> 00:09:30,628
or whether it's something you're struggling with and you sleep on it and then you wake up next morning and you've got an idea whether it's a personal problem or a problem in life and often these answers come really by just, as they say, sleeping on the problem just allowing this intelligence to give it time to sort of work out, work itself out

55
00:09:30,692 --> 00:09:36,182
And that frankly is a mystery, at least it's a mystery to me, how it does that.

56
00:09:36,984 --> 00:09:42,474
And that's another little insight into this idea of not me, not mine, not in control.

57
00:09:42,534 --> 00:09:48,325
We're not in control, not even in control of this wonderful intelligence we have.

58
00:09:48,826 --> 00:09:52,633
It has its own way of working things out.

59
00:09:54,317 --> 00:10:21,979
And so finally, you see, the Buddha himself, having gone through his own training and coming to that point of liberation, which is the liberation of this intelligence, then he begins to teach and all those things, his body, his aesthetic sense, because he likes to use imagery and stuff, and his intellect are put to the service of expressing his understandings.

60
00:10:25,013 --> 00:10:39,697
So that in summary is this word paññā, which is this fundamental basic Buddha nature we have, this intuitive intelligence.

61
00:10:39,716 --> 00:10:42,160
So I can only hope my words have been of some use.

62
00:10:42,782 --> 00:10:47,089
May you be liberated sooner rather than later.

